{"/service/ndnp/whi/batch_whi_jarlsburg_ver01/data/sn83045293/00542868880/1930071601/0451.xml":{"full_text":"Page Three\nFREIGHT RATE\nBOOST IS NEW\nFARM BURDEN\nBY LAURENCE TODD.\nStaff Correspondent\nThe Federated Press\nWASHINGTON\u2014Freight rate in\ncreases granted July 8 by the inter\nstate commerce commission to the\nrailroads, both in western trunk line\nterritory and in the east, to a total\nof $40,000,000 or more, threaten to\nadd considerably to the political\nburdens of the administration next\nNovember. For the majority of the\ncommission is as devoted to big busi\nness as is Hoover, and its findings\nin this case are that the steam rail\nroads need more money, and that\nthe return of prosperity is in sight.\nA They propose to encourage the rail\nroads at the expense of the shippers,\nat a time when wheat and other\ncrop prices have collapsed. \"Wheat\nprices are the lowest in 16 years. A\nfreight rate boost at this moment is\na heavy tax laid on the farmers,\nwho already thought themselves\nworse off than any other element of\nthe country. Political insurgency,\nwhich has risen against railroad\ndomination of the west on more than\none notable occasion, may rise again\nthis autumn.\nIncreased 25 Per Cent.\nWisconsin, lowa, northern Mis\nsouri and southeastern Minnesota\nup to the Twin Cities and Duluth,\nare ordered to pay 25 per cent more\nin freight rates than before this rul\ning was handed down. In a second\nzone, including western and north\nern Minnesota, eastern North Dako\nta, South Dakota, Nebraska and\nKansas, the increase is 12 per cent\nhigher than for Wisconsin and lowa,\non class rates. And these merchan\ndise or class rates for the third\nzone, including western North and\nSouth Dakota, Nebraska and Kan\nsas, are seven per cent higher still.\nCommissioner Porter, in a dissent\ning opinion, said that these increas\nes will in some cases amount to 100\nper cent. Such increases, he re\nmarked, are staggering. They are\nbound to put many shippers out of\nbusiness; in my 'estimation they will\nplace an undue burden upon a parti\ncular class of shipi>ers and traffic.\u201d\nWestern States Protest.\nRailroad commissions from most\nof the western states came to Wash\nington in 1927-28 and argued before\nthe interstate commerce commission\nagainst the proposed raises in inter\nstate rates. The attorney general of\nMinneosta was among the state offi\ncials who pleaded that the traffic\nin the northwest could not stand the\nhigher freight rates proposed by the\ncarriers. He said that manufactur\ning plants in that region would be\nrendered helpless to compete against\nmanufacturers in Illinois. But the\nI. C. C. has now declared that rates\nwest of Illinois are too low, and the\nrailroads are entitled to take more\nrevenue. Hence the people in those\nstates will have to pay higher prices,\nIncluding the higher freight rates,\non automobiles, radio sets, typewrit\ners, books, household goods, bakery\ngoods, heavy groceries, iron and steel\n\u201cNot Wholly Recovered.\u201d\nButter, eggs, poultry, canned\ngoods and farm implements escape\nthe general freight rate boost, be\ncause even the majority of the com\nmissioners felt that \u201cagriculture has\nnot wholly recovered from the post\nwar depression.\u201d\nWhatever the purpose of the rate\nboost when proposed in 1927, the\ncommission\u2019s grant in 1930 comes at\na time when railroad stocks are\nshaky and lean, and many railroads*\nare laying off men because of the\nhrinkage in freight traffic. The ad-\ninistration hopes that higher\naarges to shippers will, instead of\nfurther reducing the car loadings,\nsomehow promote business in the\nterritory favored by these discrim\ninations.\nDrive to Increase\nUse of Milk Urged\nA campaign to increase the milk\nconsumption of Milwaukee from .7\nof a pint a day per person to one\npint, was proposed by Health Com\nmissioner J. P. Koehler at a con\nference in his office of city health\nand welfare agency leaders late\nyesterday.\nThe conference was held to dis\ncuss means of increasing Milwau\nkee\u2019s standing in the 1930 national\nchamber of commerce health con\ntest.\nAlthough Milwaukee won first\nplace in its class in the 1929 con\ntest, it lost numerous points on cer\ntain phases of health work, Dr.\nKoehler explained.\nO K $29,500 Bids on\nMuseum Penthouse\nBids totaling ,$29,500 for the con\ntracts for building an additional\nworkroom on the roof of the public\nmuseum, were accepted by the mu\nseum board late yesterday. As only\n.$25,000 is available for the work,\nthe board will ask the board of es\ntimates for the additional $4,500\nneeded.\nTRAIN VICTIM WILL LIVE.\nAlthough he was struck by a\nfreight train, Sigfried Magnuson,\n28 years old, an. employe of the Mil\nwaukee road, was not critically in\njured last night. He was recover\ning today at County Emergency hos\npital. The accident occurred in the\nroad yards.\nBand Concert\nHUMBOLDT PARK.\nBy the Park Board band at 8 p.\nm., tomorrow, standard time. Jos\neph Gigante, director.\nCoronation March from the Prophet..\nG. Meyerbeer\nEternal City\u2014Overture ..Joseph Gigante\nMartha \u2014Selection Flotow\nCommunity singing, under the direction\nof Frederick W. Carberry.\nINTERMISSION.\nReminiscences of Scotland. .Fred Godfrey\nUntil (contralto solo) Sanderson\nMiss Elsa Bloedel.\nNorma \u2014Duet Bellini\nMiss Clementine Maley and Miss\nElsa Bloedel.\nItalian Village Scene\u2014Suite\nJoseph Gigante\n(a) The Dawn\n(b) Grand Festival Movement and\nWedding Dance\n(c) The Peasant Bove Song.\nThe Boy and the Birds.. Fred W. Hager\nfrom the Old F01k5....M. L. Lake\nAPPROVE PLANS\nFOR LAKE PARK\nGOLF COURSE\nApproval of plans for a miniature\ngolf course at Lake park was given\nby the park board last night.\nThe course will consist of 18-\nholes and will occupy about half\nof the former six-hole course in the\npark. Mashies and putters will be\nthe only clubs needed in the play\nas the greatest distance between\nholes will be 100 feet.\nWork will start at once and the\ncourse will be completed in fall, it\nis believed. The Dians were drawn\nup by Albert Riemenschneider, park\nboard engineer. He and O. W.\nSpi del, city forester, will be in\ncharge of the laying out of the\ncourse.\nBand concerts and open air park\ndances will start an end one hour\nearlier, it was voted.\nThe contract for the completion\nof the rubble mound breakwater\nnorth of Oklahoma, was awarded\nto the Edward E. Gillen Co., for\n$87,000, while Bentley Brothers,\nInc., was awarded the job of. con\nstructing 2,000 feet of protecting\nwall and ornamental walk along\nthe Juneau park waterfront for\n$63,000.\nJURIES ACQUIT\nTHIRD OF DRY\nRAID VICTIMS\nMore than a third of the defend\nants tried in criminal prohibition\ncases here by federal courts during\nthe fiscal year ending June 3 were\nacquitted, according to the report\nsent to Washington yesterday by\nLevi H. Bancroft, United States dis\ntrict attorney.\nNinety-four persons elected jury\ntrials and 34 of these were freed.\nThe government found it neces\nsary to dismiss 133 cases and dis\ncontinue prosecution in 14 others be\ncause of improper or insufficient\nevidence and absence of witnesses\nor defendants.\nCalendar Cut Greatly.\nThe calendar, which has been\ncriticized as too severe a strain for\none judge, has been reduced greatly\nand is nearer being clear than at\nany time for the last several years.\nThe report shows that at the be\nginning of the year 186 cases were\non the calendar to which 354 cases\nwere added. However, 477 cases\nwere terminated, leaving only 63 to\nbe, disposed of this fall.\n$16,000 Uncollected Fines.\nA total of 296 convictions was\nreached, 236 of these resulting from\npleas of guilty by defendants.\nCivil prohibition cases, which in\ncludes padlock actions and confisca\ntion of property, numbered 155 for\nthe year.\nFines, forfeitures and penalties\nimposed by the court during the\nyear was $69,750 of which $53,700\nactually was collected.\nNewsie Seeks Job\nIn Rich Bride's\nOld Home Town\nLOGANSPORT, Ind.\u2014Alfred Cecil\nDurban of London and his bride of\nfour months have arrived in Lo\ngansport and have taken up resi\ndence in a modest two-room apart\nment.\nMr. Durban is seeking a job as an\napprentice electrician and Mrs. Dur\nban seeks to renew old acquaint\nances. And both came here to avoid\npublicity and public discussion of\ntheir romance.\nMrs. Durban is a great-grand\ndaughter of Daniel D. Pratt, pio\nneer Logansport resident and Unit\ned States senator from Indiana. She\nwas born here as Vivienne Hunting\nton, daughter of Charles Pratt\nHuntington, millionaire. Most of\nher life was spent in London.\nFour months ago the heiress was\nmarried to Durban, 23-year-old Lon\ndoner. Their romance began when\nthe Huntington mansion in London\nwas included in the route on which\nDurban carried his daily -newspa\npers.\n13-Y ear-Old Girl\nKeeps Secret Plan\nOf Father's Death\nCENTERVILLE, la. Keep in g\nher promise to let no one know of\nbis plans for suicide, the 13-year-old\ndaughter of John Miller, 63 years\nold, farmer, Tuesday made plans to\nbury her father, dead of self ad\nministered poison.\nHe wanted a simple funeral, he\ntold the girl Sunday, after explain\ning that he intended to take his life.\nHe warned her to go to a neighbor\u2019s\nhome and spend the night and to\nreturn Monday, bringing some one\nwith her. He cautioned her to keep\nhis plans secret.\nThe girl returned Monday as di\nrected and found her father dead.\nFinancial and marital troubles were\nblamed for his act.\nMakes Suicide\nDoubly Sure With\nRope and Bullet\nIOLA. Wis.\u2014After fastening a\nrope to a rafter and tying it around\nhis neck, Lewis Nelson. GO years old,\nshot himself through the head yes\nterday.\nHe left several notes stating\nwhere his few belongings were to\ngo.\nThe fact that he had been out of\nwork for a long time was given as\nthe cause of his suicide.\nTire Blowout Kills\nTwo in Automobile\nPONTIAC, Mich.\u2014As a tire blew\nout, an automobile traveling about\n100 miles an hour plunged over the\ntop of the banked track of the Gen\neral Motors proving ground here\nTuesday. The two men in the car,\nGus Bell and Glenn McCallum, both\nof Detroit, were killed.\ni\u00dfMfiMMjj 4fc Wtf BLT LI\nw SAI\nk? d\nfa? feWv l wftf' oMv\u00bb JWWMi w am bJHI\nMt WHJto t jjj S IOP\nW EEnag AfIMMLgMIMgE w\nm||hM IL,,W S B\nW\u25a0\nOfficers and delegates to the\nWisconsin State Conference of\nPainters, held at La Crosse, July\n13 and 14, are shown above.\nFront row, left to right: Felix\nOlkives, Kenosha, vice president;\nJ. Hall, Trent Longo, fraternal\ndelegates from the Ohio State\nConference of Painters; John\nSchweigert, Milwaukee, secre-\nThe Labor Movement\nMEDICAL, BENEFIT PROVISIONS\nBACKBONE OF COMPENSATION ACT\nBY JAC. FRIEDRICH,\nLabor Editor, The Milwaukee Leader.\nEditor\u2019s Note\u2014This article is\nthe third of a series devoted to\nWisconsin\u2019s workman\u2019s compensa\ntion act, which will appear in\nThe Milwaukee Leader.\nThe main incentive actuating the\nlabor movement in its agitation for\na workman\u2019s compensation act was\nthe desire to minimize the hard\nships which industrial accidents\ncause the workers and their fam\nilies. The benefit provisions of the\nact, therefore are, at least as far\nas the workers are concerned, the\nbackbone of the law.\nThe original framers of the act\npaid very great attention to these\nprovisions and labor under the able\nleadership of the Wisconsin State\nFederation of Labor has constantly\nsought and has in many ways suc\nceeded in improving these sections\nof the law.\n65 Per Cent of Wage.\nThe law provides that compensa\ntion is to be paid at the rate of 65\nper cent of the average weekly\nwage. However, there is a maxi\nmum limit to the amount of weekly\npayments.\nIn the original law this maximum\nwas $9.37. In 1917 it was in\ncreased to $9.75, in 1919 to $14.63,\nin 1921 to $16.90, in 1923 to $18.20\nand in 1927 to $19.50.\nThis represents an increase of ex\nactly 100 per cent over the amount\nprovided for in the original act.\nThe law first provided for com\npensation payment for temporary\ndisability exclusive of the first\nweek, unless the employe was dis\nabled tfor more than four weeks, in\nwhich event he would receive com\npensation for the first week also.\nIn 1923 this was amended to allow\ncompensation for the first week if\nthe employe was still disabled at\nthe end of the third week.\nTn addition to weekly compensa-\nLabor Meetings\nTODAY.\nBricklayers, Masons, Marble Ma\nsons Protective International Union\nNo. 8, Wisconsin. 298 Fourth st.,\n7 :30 p. m.\nMarine Cooks and Stewards\u2019\nUnion of the Great Lakes. 152 Reed\nst., 2 p. m.\nFederated Trades Council of Mil\nwaukee and Vicinity, Brisbane hall,\n528 Juneau ave.\nMotion Picture Projectionists\u2019\nUnion No. 164, Alhambra hall, Wis\nconsin ave. and Fourth st., 11:30\np. m.\nPile Drivers No. 1208, Harmonie\nhall, First ave. and Mineral st., 8\np. m.\nTheatrical Stage Employes No. IS,\nMusicians\u2019 hall, 532 Edison st., 10\np. m.\nWood Carvers\u2019 Assn., room 305\nBrisbane hall, 8 p. m.\nTOMORROW.\nAuto Truck Drivers, Teamsters\nand Stablemen No. 347, Moose\nLodge hall, 44S Jefferson st., third\nfloor.\nCarpenters No. 1053 (Millmen),\nBrisbane hall, 8 p. m.\nElectrical Workers No. 494, Bues\u2019\nhall, 296 West Water st., second\nfloor, 8 p. m.\nFederal Labor Union No. 17710.\nLipp\u2019s hall. Third st. and Highland\nave., 8 p. m.\nGlass Workers Union. Local 1204.\nLipps\u2019s hall, Third st. and Highland\nave.\nLabel Trades Council Department\nA. F. of L., Room 317, 290 Third\nst., S p. m.\nMachinists Local 1052, Lipp's hall.\nThird st. and Highland ave., 7:30\np. m.\nStenographers, Bookkeepers and\nAssistants union, 16456, A. F. of L.,\n213 Alhambra building, 6 p. m.\nTerrazzo and Mosaic Workers Lo\ncal No. 20 of Wisconsin, 296 West\nWater st., 8 p. m.\nTug Firemen and Linemen Pro\ntective Assn. No. 444-4, Harmonie\nhall, 385 First ave.\n.THE MILWAUKEE LEADER, WEDNESDAY, JULY 16, 1930.\nOFFICERS, DELEGATES AT STATE CONFERENCE OF PAINTERS\ntary; Joseph J. Verchota, presi\ndent, Trades and Labor council of\nLa Crosse; Claude Downes, Lake\nGeneva, president; Carl Mullen,\nPresident, Indiana State Confer\nence of Painters; Herman Hurg\nchardt, organizer, La Crosse\nTrades and Labor council; John\nBaker, Milwaukee.\nBack row, left to right: George\nWilson, Oshkosh; Henry Klein,\nSheboygan; Edward Radtke, Mil-\ntion payments the law makes the\nemployer responsible for medical\ntreatment.\nUntil 1917 an employer was liable\nfor medical attention for only 90\ndays following an accident. In that\nyear, however, the law was amend\ned so as to authorize the industrial\ncommission to require medical at\ntention for such additional period\nof time as would tend to lesson dis\nability.\nMedical attention includes the\nnecessary medical, surgical and\nhospital treatment, medicines, med\nical and surgical supplies, crutches\nand artificial members and appli\nances.\nIf the employe desires, he may\nhave Christian Science treatment in\nlieu of medical treatment, provided\nthe employer has not filed a writ\nten notice of objection with the\ncommission.\nHave Choice of Doctor.\nUp to 1921 the employer had the\nsole right to designate the physi-\nLYNCH,HEAD 9F\nPRINTERS fOR\n14 YEARS, DIES\nSYRACUSE, N. Y.\u2014James M.\nLynch, 62 years oid, who for 14\nyears was president of the Interna\ntional Typographical union, died\ntoday in a hospital here, a victim\nof blood infection.\nHe had been in poor health the\nlast few years, a sufferer from dia\nbetes. A few months ago, Ji sub\nmitted to an operation on one of\nhis feet, which included amputation\nof a toe.\nElected in 1900.\nLynch, who was widely known in\nthe organized labor movement\nthroughout the United States and\nCanada, was one of the leaders in\nthe campaign promoted from 1907\nto 1909, which resulted in realiza\ntion of the 48-hour work week for\nunion printers.\nHe was first elected president of\nthe printers in their convention in\nMilwaukee, in 1900 and held that\nposition until 1913, when he resigned\nto accept the post of labor com\nmissioner of New York, to which\nhe was appointed by Gov. Martin\nGlynn. Subsequently he was one of\nNew York state\u2019s four industrial\ncommissioners.\nEdited Labor Paper.\nLynch was elected president of\nthe printers again in 1924 and\nserved until November, 1926, having\nbeen defeated in his campaign for\nre-election by Charles F. Howard\nof Chicago.\nA long-time resident of Syracuse,\nLynch was editor and publisher of\na labor paper in that city for a\nnumber of years.\nLynch was known to many mem\nbers of Milwaukee Typographical\nunion No. 23. He made his last\nvisit to Milwaukee during 1924, on\nwhich occasion he spoke at a ban\nquet in his honor in the Wisconsin\nhotel, arranged by the local union.\nEmployment Drops\nAgain in New York\nBy Federated Press.\nNEW YORK\u2014 A further drop of\n2 per cent in factory employment\nfor June was reported by the New\nlork State Department of Labor, al\nthough employment usually changes\nvery little between May and June.\nThe June index number of factory\nemployment in New York state\ndropped to 86.7, the lowest point\never recorded since records began in\n1914. The number of workers in\niron and steel dropped 8.4 per cent\nand automobiles and airplanes 11.4\nper c^t.\nwaukee; Elmer Hamsun, Madi\nson; C. A. Roethe, State Board of\nVocational Education; C. Hanson,\nRacine; Theodore Heideman, La\nCrosse; George Brock, Neenah;\nCharles Bader, Green Bay; Otto\nMesenbrink, Milwaukee: Oliver\nRichie, Janesville; E. E. Gunn,\nJr., State Board of Vocational\nEducation; F. H. McClain, Madi\nson, and Frank J. Janda, Osh\nkosh.\ncian or surgeon who would treat an\ninjured employe, but in that year\nthe employe was given the right to\na selection from a panei of compe\ntent doctors.\nEvery employer is required to\npost a list of the names and ad\ndresses of the physicians on his pan\nel so as to give his employes an\nopportunity to make their choice.\nBesides the provisions for week\nly compensation payments for tem\nporary disability and medical treat\nment the law provides for compen\nsation for permanent disability\nwhether such disability be partial\nor total.\nAllowances Discussed Next.\nTlie original law provided for\ncompensation for permanent disabil\nity according to the extent of the\nwage loss, if such disability led to\na wage loss.\nThe administrative problems of\ndetermining such wage loss were so\ngreat, howeve^, that in 1913 a sched\nule of allowances for various types\nof permanent disabilities was\nadopted to be paid regardless of\nwhether or not they led to wage\nloss.\nThis schedule of allowances for\nipermanent disability and its appli\ncation will be the subject of the\nnext article.\nFormer President\nOf Printers Dies\n\n\nJAMES M. LYNCH.\nOur eyes are capable of receiving\nand \u201ctaking in\u201d properly 10 impres\nsions in the space of a second.\nUNION MADE and\nHo\nA\nM\nr s\nif. feMWI\n1 jagagj^^\ni\nx y7\nJ\nAT YOUR DEALER\nor\nPhone Marquette 7300\nSchuster's\nr r gakfiixlD 12^ *rr vutev aaitchelu at 6\n__U\ni\n4 Valuable Schuster Stamps With Every 10c Cash Purchase\nMEN! Qreat Special Purchase!\n2-Pants SUITS\nM lB- 50\nWP fl ru y Outstanding Values!\n|i' w I Now! Here is the chance to buy that\nJ I su you ve een thinking about! Ordi-\nnarily you would have to pay much\nI %X J more for such wonderfully well made,\n_ bard w clothes. Real values!\n\u25a0l \u00dfeal quality! A real chance to save!\nHwN B 5 Come in, see the good-looking wor-\nsi! steds and cassimeres, note the broad\nshoulders, snug hips. Two trousers\nft'S I with everv suit. Sizes 36 to 44. Buy\nS- Thursday!\nlw Clearance! $19.95 Tropical\nf-O l Worsteds, Now Reduced to\n\"VSJtSK S' I Now in the middle of a\nM MKL,. the hot summer season, f W 